I would like to request an option to make the JavaScript formatter place an `else` on its own line. There does not appear to be an option for this in the vscode settings so far. Consider the following as an example:

```js
if (x) {
    console.log('foo');
}
else {
    console.log('bar');
}
```

Currently, the JavaScript formatter converts this into the following:

```js
if (x) {
    console.log('foo');
} else {
    console.log('bar');
}
```

Note that this behavior is also inconsistent with the TypeScript formatter which formats the latter code into the former format.

- VSCode Version: 1.8.1
- OS Version: Windows 10

I was writing an extension yesterday and faced an interesting error. I tried to use TextEditorEdit.delete() as first class function inside `.forEach` but it just failed with message `Running the contributed command:'extension.hungryDelete' failed.` I solved the problem with explicitly specifying the callback function. Is it a bug or just a feature of typescript?

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Download the source code at `https://github.com/Jasonlhy/VSCode-Hungry-Delete` and open it in VSCode
2. Replace

```ts
let result = editor.edit((editorBuilder) => {
            deleteRanges.forEach((deleteRange) => {
                 editorBuilder.delete(deleteRange);
            });
        });
```

with

```ts
let result = editor.edit((editorBuilder) => {
           deleteRanges.forEach(editorBuilder.delete);
        });
```

3. `npm install` and run the project
4. Add some text in the testing environment
```
    222

    333
```
5. Press `ctrl + backspace` to execute the command
